{
  "texts": [
    "monomorphism);(2) the subcategories contain all isomorphisms; and, (3) every morphism in C factors uniquely (up to isomorphism) as a morphism in E followed by a morphism in M.If C is a finite skeletal category, it follows that for each object 𝑐 ∈ C Aut(𝑐) = E(𝑐, 𝑐) = M(𝑐, 𝑐), where E(𝑐, 𝑑):= C(𝑐, 𝑑) ∩ E ⊆ Epi(𝑐, 𝑑) and M(𝑐, 𝑑):= C(𝑐, 𝑑) ∩ M ⊆ Mono(𝑐, 𝑑), see e.g., [YOT18, Lemma 1.3].",
    "We may define |C| × |C|-matrices that record the data of an epi-mono factorization system (E, M): the epimorphism matrix 𝐸 is defined by 𝐸 𝑐𝑑 = |E(𝑐, 𝑑)|/|Aut(𝑑)|, the monomorphism matrix 𝑀 is defined by 𝑀 𝑐𝑑 = |M(𝑐, 𝑑)|/|Aut(𝑐)|, and, the automorphism matrix 𝐴 is defined by 𝐴 𝑐𝑑 = |Aut(𝑐)|𝛿 𝑐𝑑, where 𝛿 𝑐𝑑 is the Kronecker delta.",
    "Despite being defined as rational numbers, the entries of these matrices are integral: for example, for the epimorphism matrix this follows since the automorphism group Aut(𝑑) acts freely on E(𝑐, 𝑑) by the cancellation property of epimorphisms.",
    "The case for the monomorphism matrix is dual.",
    "Moreover, since Aut(𝑐) = E(𝑐, 𝑐) = M(𝑐, 𝑐), we have that 𝐸 𝑐𝑐 = 1 = 𝑀 𝑐𝑐 for each 𝑐 ∈ C. Lemma 2.3 ([Yos87, Lemma 4.1])."
  ]
}